# Exercise – Record Video on macOS (Camtasia Recorder Only)

This exercise covers the **macOS‑only** portion of the workflow.  
The Mac is used **only** as a recording device using **Camtasia Recorder**.  
No editing is performed on macOS.  
No `.tscproj` files are created or saved.

All dehydration and editing occur on Windows.

---

# Goals
1. Prepare the Mac for recording  
1. Launch Camtasia **Recorder Only**  
1. Record the lesson  
1. Perform VLC sanity checks  
1. Create the project ZIP (Mac‑exact doctrine)  
1. Upload ZIP to Dropbox (browser only)  
1. Return macOS to a stateless condition  

---

# Prepare the Mac for Recording

1. **Close all unnecessary applications**  
   - Only the recording target (browser, terminal, IDE, etc.) should remain open.

1. **Ensure external monitor is connected (if used)**  
   - Camtasia Recorder must capture the **exact monitor** you intend to record.

---

# Launch Camtasia Recorder (macOS)

1. Launch **Camtasia** from Applications (Spotlight: `Command + Space → Camtasia`).  
2. Camtasia opens to:
   ```
   “Welcome to Camtasia Editor, <your name>!”
   ```
   This is expected.

---

# Determine the Correct Path to the Recorder

Camtasia on macOS has two possible UI states.

---

## **Case A — “New Recording” is visible on the Welcome screen**
If you see:
```
New Recording
```
→ **Click it immediately.**  
→ Skip “New Project.”  
→ Skip all Editor UI.  
→ Go directly to the Recorder.

This is the **fast path**.

---

## **Case B — “New Recording” is NOT visible**
You MUST enter the Editor **only** to expose the top menu bar.

1. Click:
   ```
   New Project
   ```
   This opens the Editor window.

1. In the top menu bar, click:
   ```
   File → New Recording…
   ```

This launches **Camtasia Recorder**, which is the only tool used on macOS.

**Important:**  
- You will not save anything in the Editor.  
- You will not touch the timeline or media bin.  
- You will not create or save a `.tscproj`.  
- The Editor is only a doorway to the Recorder.

---

# Configure Recording Region  
(Camtasia Recorder must be open before this step.)

1. Select the **monitor** you want to capture.  
   - Operators must capture **only one monitor**, never “All Screens.”
2. Confirm the green bounding box matches the intended display.

---

# Configure Audio Input  
(Camtasia Recorder must be open before this step.)

1. Select the correct microphone from the dropdown.  
2. Speak a few words and confirm the input meter moves.

---

# Configure System Audio  
(Camtasia Recorder must be open before this step.)

1. Locate the **System Audio** toggle in the Recorder window.

2. Choose based on your recording intent:

   - **If you want system audio recorded**  
     Toggle **System Audio: On**.  
     Use this when the lesson requires capturing application sounds, browser audio, or demo audio.

   - **If you only want your voice recorded**  
     Toggle **System Audio: Off**.  
     This prevents macOS notification beeps, background sounds, and application noises from being captured.

3. Confirm the toggle reflects your intended recording mode before starting the lesson.

---

# Start Recording

1. Position all windows exactly as they should appear in the video.  
   - Browser, terminal, IDE, and any other on‑screen elements should be in their final layout.

2. In the Camtasia Recorder window, click the **big red button** labeled:
   ```
   rec
   ```

3. Wait for the countdown (if enabled).  

4. Present your Show and Tell demonstration.

---

# Stop Recording

1. Click the big red **rec** button again in the Recorder control bar.

2. Camtasia will open **Camtasia Rev**, the lightweight review window.  
   **This is expected. Do not save anything here. Do not touch anything here.**

3. In Camtasia Rev, click:
   ```
   Open in Editor
   ```
   This opens the **full Camtasia Editor** (the version with the timeline).

4. In the Editor, you should see the **start of your recorded video** in the Preview pane.  
   Click **PLAY** and watch/listen for **5–10 seconds**.  
   This quick sanity check catches:  
   - wrong screen recorded  
   - no audio (mic unplugged, wrong input, etc.)  
   - notification beeps  
   - corrupted start  

   **Happy Path:**  
   - If everything looks and sounds correct, continue to the Save the Recording step.

   **“It’s Crap” Path:**  
   - Quit Camtasia completely:  Camtasia menu → Quit Camtasia.  
   - When macOS asks:  “Do you want to keep this new document ‘Untitled’?”  
     click the **Delete** button.  
   - Relaunch Camtasia and begin the recording process again.

---

# Save the Recording to the RAW Folder

1. When the **Save Recording** dialog appears, set the **file name**:
   ```
   lesson_01.trec
   ```

2. Set the **path**:
   ```
   ~/dev/catools-lc/ACTIVE/RAW/
   ```

3. Click:
   ```
   Save
   ```

After this step, the `.trec` file is safely written to disk in the correct RAW folder.

---

# Sanity Check the Recording (VLC Only)

1. Open **Finder** and navigate to:
   ```
   ~/dev/catools-lc/ACTIVE/RAW/
   ```
1. **Right‑click**:
   ```
   lesson_01.trec
   ```
1. Choose:
   ```
   Open With → VLC
   ```
1. Play 5–10 seconds.

Confirm:
- Video exists  
- Audio exists  
- No corruption  
- No silence  
- No stutter  

If any issue is found, re‑record immediately.

---

# Create the Project ZIP (Mac‑Exact Doctrine)

The ZIP must contain **exactly one top‑level folder named `catools-lc`**, matching Linux and Windows.

**Important:**  
To achieve this structure on macOS, you must compress the **entire `catools-lc` folder**, not the subfolders.

1. In **Finder**, navigate to the parent folder that contains:
   ```
   catools-lc
   ```

   For example:
   ```
   ~/dev/
   ```

1. **Right‑click** the folder:
   ```
   catools-lc
   ```
1. Choose:
   ```
   Compress "catools-lc"
   ```

1. Finder creates:
   ```
   catools-lc.zip
   ```

Resulting structure inside the ZIP:

```
catools-lc.zip
    catools-lc/
        ACTIVE/
        ROLLBACK_VAULT/
```

This is the **only** acceptable structure.

---

# Upload ZIP to Dropbox (Browser Only)

1. Open a browser.  
1. Navigate to:
   ```
   https://www.dropbox.com/home/caTools/LearningCurve/lesson_01/
   ```
1. Upload:
   ```
   ~/dev/catools-lc.zip
   ```

Confirm the upload completes without errors.

---

# Tidy Up the Mac (Stateless Doctrine)

1. In **Finder**, delete the working folder:
   ```
   ~/dev/catools-lc/
   ```
1. Delete the ZIP:
   ```
   ~/dev/catools-lc.zip
   ```

The Mac now holds **no local project state**.  
All project assets live in Dropbox and will be processed on Windows.

---

# End of Mac Recording Exercise

This completes the macOS‑only recording workflow.  
Dehydration and editing occur on Windows in the next exercise.
